  "market_context": "After a Judas swing up post-midnight open where London formed the high of day, the analyst was looking for a downside continuation toward sell-side liquidity. An SMT divergence between ES and NQ was already in place at the session high as confluence to the reversal.",
  "key_observation": "Even while analyzing on the 1-hour chart, a lower time frame SMT can be spotted by examining individual wicks: at the 11:00 low, ES took out the prior low while NQ did not, exposing a 5-minute SMT divergence that aligned with the higher time frame reversal.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the higher time frame setup — Judas swing up after midnight open, London high of day, and SMT divergence at the highs anticipating a move lower to sell-side liquidity.",
    "Step 2: Confirmed price did reach for the sell-side lows, validating that the SMT served as confluence (not the primary cause) for the reversal.",
    "Step 3: Examined the 11:00 low wick on both ES and NQ on the 1-hour chart and noted ES swept the prior low while NQ did not — a divergence visible from the higher time frame.",
    "Step 4: Dropped down to the 5-minute chart to verify: ES made a lower low while NQ made a higher low at the same 11:00 timestamp, confirming a lower time frame SMT.",
    "Step 5: Concluded this LTF SMT added confluence to the reversal and explained the methodology of locating LTF SMTs from an HTF chart at session highs/lows, PDH/PDL, and HTF levels."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reversed and reached sell-side liquidity as anticipated; the high was not violated.",
  "lessons": "SMTs are everywhere, but only matter when they align with a higher time frame level or idea (session highs/lows, PDH/PDL, HTF PD arrays). Lower time frame SMTs can be detected from HTF wicks and used as reversal confluence — never as a standalone signal.",
